data.content:
All three code snippets hit EF Core 10 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and the fixes:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — expression tree no longer compiles

EF 10 changed the parameter from `Expression<Func<...>>` to `Func<...>`. Your manual expression-tree building won't compile. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. — the whole point of the change was to make dynamic setters trivial.

---

### 2. Complex type columns — two breaking changes

**a) Column name uniquification:** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared one `Street` column. EF 10 auto-appends a number (e.g. `Street1`) to disambiguate. If you intentionally share the column, pin it explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex type full-path naming:** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was previously mapped to column `BillingAddress_City`. EF 10 now uses the full path: `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

**Either way**, generate a new migration and inspect it carefully — the column renames will show up as `RenameColumn` operations. If you already have data, make sure to review before applying.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Add it to your implementation:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
